(And now I forgive the use of 50 as the East Coast representative, because the rest of the people I mentioned weren't beneficiaries of Dre's work, whereas everyone else on stage was.) 

This was a fucking great halftime show. And I don't think I'm just saying that because I'm old

Huh, so between "Forgot About Dre" and the finale, it seems like the actual feature artist here was Dre, and I kind of love that, because it was a showcase of his many talents: MC, producer for everyone on stage, a keen ear for talent, and a guy happy to share the spotlight.
And yeah, taking the knee was cool and relieved the Black artists from getting harassed about it by legions of MAGA goons. So that was nice.

I don't especially love Eminem (his frequently homophobic and misogynistic lyrics are a bridge too far even for someone who loves a lot of retrospectively problematic 90's rap), but if you think he's not talented, try "Lose Yourself" at karaoke sometime and be humbled.

Kendrick demonstrating why he is going to be held in as high a regard in 20 years as his elders are right now. Just an absolute monster talent. Phenomenal flow, incredible stage presence, just a consummate performer.

Sorry, I have nothing coherent to say about Mary J. Blige absolutely tearing the fucking roof off of the entire PLANET with "Family Affair" and "No More Drama," my GOD. I miss those absolute club bangers that were also incredible, vocal showcasing ballads. Bring those back!

Though Ice-T, Nas, DMX, Busta Rhymes, most of Wu-Tang, and even KRS-One I'd argue were big enough to warrant consideration here. I think Queen Latifah or Lil' Kim would have been nice East Coast reps (but I can understand if the latter didn't want to share a stage with Dre)

It was also a way for Dre to sidestep being on stage with anyone from the late 90s NYC scene during the East Coast/West Coast wars. Though, of course, most of the big (and Big*) crossover artists are all dead, now, sadly. 

(RIP Biggie, Big Pun, and Big L, the holy trinity)
The inclusion of 50 Cent here as the representative of East Coast has to be down to him being "discovered" by Eminem and basically made famous by his and Dre's production on Get Rich or Die Trying.

Also, wow, the "California Love" video was very formative to my budding sexuality when it came out a couple weeks shy of my 15th birthday, because literally every single person who appears on screen in it looks both incredibly fucking cool and extremely attractive. https://t.co/8U5oEjQDd3

A lot has been made of this being the most Gen X halftime show ever, and wow, does "California Love" really drive home that this was the *Xennial* halftime show. For 1995 teens and college kids, this song was ubiquitous at every school dance and club for YEARS.
Kinda loved that Snoop's song is actually a Dre song on which Snoop was featured, and that Dre's does "California Love," which was a song on which he was featured. Nice little rhyme there.

First of all, LOVE the giant desk for Dre when the show opens. The man is one of the greatest producers of all time, and that's such a "hidden" artform, and I love that they're giving it the very public celebration it deserves.
